basic options were to sell the inventory and abandon the brand or to find a way to carry on to understand the value of the family business olivier reza had to evaluate the inventory the house’s history and the wealth of drawings and records in the company’s archiveshaving excluded the idea of selling he had to come up with a revival strategy to start he decided to shrink the business closing its five stores worldwide photo a “rose perlée” necklace designed by alexandre reza in  it has a yellow diamond at its center and five strands of natural pearls credit courtesy of alexandre reza “the real métier of haute joaillerie as it was established by louis cartier frédéric boucheron laurence graff jacques arpels and my father draws primarily on passion” olivier reza said in an interview in the ornate firstfloor salons of the thcentury hôtel de fontpertuis that the jeweler occupies on the place vendôme “practically that means you must be able to invest tens of millions in precious stones and really believe in what you are doing“after the war my father was able to purchase quantities of natural and untreated stones in ceylon and burma” he said referring to today’s sri lanka and myanmar “the reza house currently possesses one of the world’s largest inventories of unheated and untreated colored gemstones when you sit on a fortune like that you need vision and passion and you cannot be in a hurry”he added “we liberated ourselves from retail pressure to concentrate on creation now we have the luxury of time and can take eight to  months to produce a piece without worrying about the rent” the firm has spent three years designing a new collection with a team of four outsourcing production to three workshops here the show that represents the culmination of his efforts mixes old and new it includes  historic pieces from the past  years showcasing the stones and craftsmanship that made alexandre reza a celebrated name there are  new pieces in a more contemporary style “mostly unique that creatively speaking were made from scratch” olivier reza said “through that process i have realized i have a preference for geometric shapes” newsletter sign up continue reading the main story please verify youre not a robot by clicking the box invalid email address please reenter you must select a newsletter to subscribe to sign up you agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for the new york timess products and services thank you for subscribing an error has occurred please try again later you are already subscribed to this email view all new york times newsletters see sample manage email preferences not you privacy policy opt out or contact us anytime alexandre reza “was a connoisseur of highquality stones and brought many exceptional ones to france” said marguerite de cerval a jewelry historian in paris “his technique remained traditional but he had a style and flair that appealed to an international clientele”the house was particularly known for parures and the show includes several matching pieces notably a set featuring  carats of untreated colombian emeralds and earrings set with  carats of ceylon sapphires and diamonds“some of the parures have  stones of over  carats each all in the same color” olivier reza saidalexandre reza also made a specialty of “trembleuse” or articulated jewelry a carat burmese sapphire ring set atop  diamonds is a striking example of his work “the mount is invisible you see only the diamonds” his son said advertisement continue reading the main story “alexandre used to say that the stone drove jewelry design” ms de cerval said “some of olivier’s designs are innovative but others remain on his father’s path it remains to be seen whether he will succeed in departing from the house’s traditional formulas” continue reading the main story we’re interested in your feedback on this page tell us what you think whats next loading go to home page » site index the new york times olivier reza profiles  facebook facebookemail 